710728f-a.title: Manhattan: 11th Avenue - 54th Street
710728f-a.text:
Eleventh Avenue, north from and including 54th Street.
Eleventh Avenue, with the railnoad running down it from 60th Street,
used to be nicknamed "DDeath Avenue"; but by the time of this
picture the danger is more from the automobiles.
A steam locomotive is shown here; in five more years these will be
superseded by Diesel engines.
May 20, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.

713745f-b.title: Manhattan: 54th Street (West) - 11th Avenue
713745f-b.text:
West 54th Strcet, west from, but not including Eleventh Ave., to,
but not including the Hudson River, showing in the foreground, the De Witt]
Clinton Park. The ditch on the west, will eventually be Twelfth Ave.
August 29, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.
The same, from a different angle.

713746f-a.title: Manhattan: 54th Street (West) - 11th Avenue
713746f-a.text:
West 54th Street, west from Eleventh Ave., to the North (Hudson) River.
Shown on the left is the north side of De Witt Clinton Park.
May 6, 1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Art Project.
